{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}
'''Sir Bernard Hale''' (1677–1729) was an English-born  [[barrister]]  and judge who became [[Chief Baron of the Irish Exchequer]]. Two of his sons became Generals  in the British Army.<ref>Ball, F. Elrington  ''The Judges in Ireland 1221–1921''  London  John Murray 1926</ref>

==Background==
He was born at [[King's Walden]], [[Hertfordshire]], the  eighth son of William Hale and his wife Mary Elwes. The Hale family, who  originally made their fortune as [[grocers]]  in London,  had owned property in King's Walden since the sixteenth century,<ref>{{cite DNB|last=Rigg|first=J. M.|wstitle=Hale, Bernard|volume=24|page=17}}</ref> and Bernard's own descendants were still living there in Victorian times.<ref>Baker, J. H.  \Bernard Hale\"

